Because you mentioned it&#39;s for java 8, I didn&#39;t suggest on using `takeWhile`, which was added to jdk9. But if you&#39;re interested, read about it as well:
https://stackoverflow.com/a/46850795/12769096

While there is a method `takeWhile` that stops the iteration when a condition is met for the *particular* element iterated, there is, unfortunately, nothing implemented stopping the iteration when a criterion is met for the aggregated result such as `reduceWhile` or `collectWhile`.

There is a similar [question][1] that you can adapt to your use-case:

1. Implement a custom `Spliterator` that stops yielding elements while a condition is met:

      ```java
      public class StoppingSpliterator&lt;T&gt; extends Spliterators.AbstractSpliterator&lt;T&gt; {

          private final Spliterator&lt;T&gt; spliterator;
          private final Supplier&lt;Boolean&gt; stopCondition;

          public StoppingSpliterator(Spliterator&lt;T&gt; spliterator, Supplier&lt;Boolean&gt; stopCondition) {
              super(spliterator.estimateSize(), 0);
              this.spliterator = spliterator;
              this.stopCondition = stopCondition;
          }

          @Override
          public boolean tryAdvance(Consumer&lt;? super T&gt; action) {
              if (stopCondition.get()) {
                  return false;
              }
              return spliterator.tryAdvance(action);
          }
      }
      ```

2. Define the limit and the accumulator:

      ```java
      final int n = 4;
      final AtomicInteger accumulator = new AtomicInteger();
      ```
3. Perform the reduction on the `Stream` wrapped in the `StoppingSpliterator`

      ```java
      final var result = StreamSupport
              .stream(new StoppingSpliterator&lt;&gt;(
                      authors.spliterator(), 
                      () -&gt; accumulator.get() &gt; n), false)
              .reduce(accumulator,
                      (i, author) -&gt; {
                          System.out.println(&quot;Iterating: &quot; + author.getName());
                          i.addAndGet(author.getBooks().size());
                          return i;
                      },
                      (x, y) -&gt; null);

      // get the result
      System.out.println(result.get() &gt; n);
      ```

Here are some test data assuming the full-args constructor `(String name, List&lt;String&gt; books)` and getters of the class `Author`.

```java
List&lt;Author&gt; authors = List.of(
    new Author(&quot;Tom&quot;, List.of(&quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;c&quot;)),
    new Author(&quot;Bob&quot;, List.of()),
    new Author(&quot;Sam&quot;, List.of(&quot;a&quot;)),
    new Author(&quot;Kim&quot;, List.of()),
    new Author(&quot;Tim&quot;, List.of(&quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;)),
    new Author(&quot;Pim&quot;, List.of(&quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;c&quot;, &quot;d&quot;, &quot;e&quot;)));
```

The iteration stops when the sum of books is larger than `n`: `4` in our case, so the last iterated author is `Tim` who is an author of a further book so the sum would be 5. If you remove the last 2-3 authors or empty their books, the whole list is iterated as the stopping condition is not met to the very end.

_____

**Disclaimer**: I particularly dislike this solution for multiple reasons:

1. It is hard to implement, read, and debug.
2. It mutates `AtomicInteger` accumulator defined outside the `Stream`.
3. I doubt the whole thing can work in parallel.
4. You can use a for-loop with `break` or a `while` loop:

   ```java
   final Iterator&lt;Author&gt; iterator = authors.iterator();
