Since the Kotlin compiler take [Java nullability annotations][1] (like jsr305  @Nullable) into account, you could annotate your java methods with such annotations to obtain the desired behavior.

    public class JavaClass {
      @CheckForNull
      public String getString() {
        return null;
      }
    }

This can be done at the package level via package-info.java files.

    @CheckForNull
    package mypackage;

Note that it could be better to reverse this logic: use package-info to annotate all methods as returning non-null and specify only the nullable ones as in the first code sample above. This would gain you the same kind of null-safety on the java side a on the kotlin side, assuming you use one of the tools available to enforce these annotations.

(from [baeldung][2])

    @NonNullApi
    package mypackage;


  [1]: https://kotlinlang.org/docs/java-interop.html#nullability-annotations
  [2]: https://www.baeldung.com/java-package-info

