I feel that this is due to the type erasure that happens at compile time. This line in `BaseAction` class `TypeReference&lt;RT&gt; typeRef = new TypeReference&lt;RT&gt;() {}` will have a &quot;memory&quot; of only &quot;child class of `BaseResult`&quot; and not **which** particular child class. Since each child may have a different structure, you cannot safely cast the parent to it.

Hence, you can either:
- Provide a `Deserializer` to `BaseResult`, which will have handling for the different implementations, OR
- Provide an abstract method in `BaseResult` to get the implemented type. This can be passed to `readValue(..)` instead of `TypeReference&lt;..&gt;`, as shown below (not compiled or tested, only for indication of the idea):
```java
public abstract class BaseAction&lt;IT extends BaseInput, RT extends BaseResult&gt; {
    /* Method to the get the actual type */
    protected Class&lt;RT&gt; getImplClass();

    public RT execute(final IT inObj) throws Exception {
        //...
        return JacksonFunctions.jacksonObjectMapper.readValue(jsonString, getImplClass());
    }
}
```
```java
public class MyAction extends BaseAction&lt;MyInput, MyResult&gt; {
    protected Class&lt;MyResult&gt; getImplClass(){
        return MyResult.class;
    }
}
```

